rNames><gtr:surname>Stewart</gtr:surname><gtr:orcidId>0000-0002-9891-9028</gtr:orcidId><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=RES-173-27-0116"><gtr:id>4DF3CE25-D14E-410A-90A9-AF539A57FE9E</gtr:id><gtr:title>The use of consumer views in evaluating the performance of government programmes</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>RES-173-27-0116</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>The Economic and Social Research Council (ESRC) and the National Audit Office (NAO) awarded a fellowship to Dr Ruth Stewart (Institute of Education, London) to work within the NAO. The NAO looks at how government spends taxpayers' money and each year undertakes 60 major reports exploring whether government services provide value for money. This fellowship aimed to review and improve the ways in which the NAO collects and analyses consumers' views for their 'Value for Money' reports. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>Using an action research approach in which research is conducted alongside a process of trying out and evaluating new techniques, this project incorporated the systematic review of documents, as well as interviews with those involved. This project fed into advice for study teams, guidance materials and a seminar programme, as well as external publications. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>In addition this fellowship has provided opportunities for developing the NAO's use of qualitative research methods.&lt;/p>

